LDS._0475_02_Tu__OH_TRO_VED_SE_C_UNA_SPI_COM_["eng"] = u"(... Oh, found it! Let's see if there's an understandable explanation...)"
LDS._0475_03_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_IN_QUE_LEZ_INI_A_TRA_IL_MOD_DEL_MOT_UNI_ACC_BR_UN_MO_RET_UNI_ACC__UN_TIP_DI_MOT_IN_CUI_UN_COR_SI_MUO_LUN_UNA_LIN_RET_CON_ACC_COS_["eng"] = u"In this lesson we will begin to explore the uniformly accelerated motion model... <br> A \"uniformly accelerated rectilinear motion\" is a type of motion in which a body moves along a straight line with constant acceleration."
LDS._0475_04_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_LE_FOR_CHE_SI_USA_PER_CAL_GLI_ESI_DI_QUE_TIP_DI_MOT_VEN_CHI_LE_ORA_DEL_MOT_RET_UNI_ACC_E_SON_PRI_DUE_BR_VF__VI__A_BR_S__VI__12_["eng"] = u"The formulas used to calculate the outcomes of these types of motion are called \"hourly law of uniform rectilinear motion\" and are mainly two: <br> <*>#italic#Vf = Vi + A×T<*> <br> <*>#italic#S = Vi×T + (1/2)×A×T²<*>"
LDS._0475_05_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_DOV_VF__LA_VEL_DEL_COR_IN_MET_AL_SEC_NEL_FIN_VI__LA_VEL_DEL_COR_IN_MET_AL_SEC_NEL_INI_A__LAC_IN_MET_AL_SEC_QUA_CHE_IL_COR_MAN_TRA_LEV_INI_E_LEV_FIN_T__IL_TEM_CHE_PAS_IN_SEC_TRA_LEV_INI_E_LEV_FIN_S__LO_SPA_PER_DAL_COR_IN_MET_TRA_LEV_INI_E_LEV_FIN_["eng"] = u"Where: <*>#italic#Vf<*> is the body speed (in meters per second) at the final event; <*>#italic#Vi<*> is the body speed (in meters per second) at the initial event; <*>#italic#A<*> is the acceleration (in meters per square second) that the body maintains between the initial event and the final event; <*>#italic#T<*> is the time that passes (in seconds) between the initial event and the final event; <*>#italic#S<*> is the space traveled by the body (in meters) between the initial event and the final event."
LDS._0475_06_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_OSS_SUL_FOR_DEL_MOT_UNI_ACC_["eng"] = u"Observations on the uniformly accelerated motion formulas..."
LDS._0475_07_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_LA_PRI_EQU_DET_QUA__LA_REL_TRA_VEL_ACC_E_TEM_LA_DIF_DI_VEL_TRA_LEV_INI_E_QUE_FIN_DIP_DA_QUA_LAC_E_PER_QUA_TEM_ESS_VIE_APP_LA_SEC_FOR_INV_ESP_LA_DIS_PER_DA_UN_COR_IN_UN_DET_LAS_DI_TEM_IN_CUI_VIE_IMP_UNA_COS_["eng"] = u"The first equation determines the relationship between speed, acceleration and time: the difference in speed between the initial and the final event depends on how much acceleration is involved and for how long it is applied. The second formula expresses the distance travelled by a body in a certain period of time in which a constant acceleration is applied."
LDS._0475_08_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_ESE_SUL_MOT_RET_UNI_ACC_["eng"] = u"Examples on uniformly accelerated rectilinear motion..."
LDS._0475_09_Tu_VED_SE_CE_N_UNO_SIM_ALL_MIA_SIT_["eng"] = u"(Let's see if there's one similar to my situation...)"
LDS._0475_10_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_UN_CAR_DI_CAV_VIA_A_6_MS_SE_IL_CAR_RAL_CON_UNA_DEC_ACC_NEG_COS_DI_2_MS_QUA_SPA_PER_PRI_DI_FER_["eng"] = u"A horse wagon travels at 6 m/s. If the wagon slows down with a constant deceleration (negative acceleration) of 2 m/s², how much does it travel before stopping?"
LDS._0475_11_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_LA_VEL_INI_DEL_CAR__VI__6_MS_BR_LA_VEL_FIN_DAT_CHE_SI_DEV_FER__VF__0_MS_BR_LAC_DAT_CHE__CON_ALL_DIR_DEL_CAR__NEG_A__2_MS_["eng"] = u"The initial speed of the wagon is: <*>#italic#Vi = 6 m/s.<*> <br> The final speed, since it eventually stops, is: <*>#italic#Vf = 0 m/s.<*> <br> The acceleration, since it is opposite to the direction of the wagon, is negative: <*>#italic#A = -2 m/s².<*>"
LDS._0475_12_LibroMotoRettilineoUniformementeAccelerato_PRI_DI_TUT__NEC_RIC_IL_TEM_CHE_IMP_IL_CAR_PER_FER_BR_DAL_REL_VF__VI__A_SI_OTT_T__VF__VI__A_BR_SOS_CON_I_DAT_CHE_ABB_T__0__6__2__3_BR_PER_FER_IL_CAR_IMP_3_SEC_["eng"] = u"First of all, we need to determine how long it takes the wagon to stop. <br> From the equation <*>#italic#Vf = Vi + A×T,<*> we get: <*>#italic#T = (Vf - Vi) / A.<*> <br> Filling it with the data we have: <*>#italic#T = (0 - 6) / (-2) = 3.<*> <br> It takes 3 seconds for the wagon to stop."
