LDS._0986_01_Tu_QUE_LIB_SIN_SU_COS_VOL__TEM_["eng"] = u"(This book is called: \"On Consciousness Vol.3 - Time\"...)"
LDS._0986_02_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol3Tempo__SVI_LIP_PER_CUI_LA_REA_SI_EVO_IN_MOD_DET_VIE_SPO_CHI_IN_CHE_MOD_IL_TEM_SCO_IN_AVA_POT_CON_DUE_POS_IL_TEM__COM_DA_UN_SUS_DI_EVE_DET_E_SEP_TRA_LOR_OPP_DA_UN_FL_INF_DI_EVE_IND_E_INS_TRA_LOR_["eng"] = u"... Considering the hypothesis for which reality it's determined, one might wonder how comes time goes forward. We could consider two scenarios. One: time is a succession of events which are determined and independent. Two: time is like an infinite \"flow\" of events which are indistinguishable and inseparable from one other."
LDS._0986_03_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol3Tempo__PRE_LA_PRI_IPO_IN_CUI_GLI_EVE_SON_DIS_E_SEP_DOV_IPO_CHE_TRA_UN_EVE_E_LAL_CI_SIA_UN_MO_IN_CUI_IL_TEM_NON_SCO_MA_IN_CUI_AVV_UN_QUA_COS_CHE_PER_ALL_SUC_DI_AVV_DOV_IPO_CHE_CI_SIA_UNA_SOR_DI_MO_IMM_CHE_SEN_ESS_MOS_O_CA_DA_ALT_EVE_RIE_A_FAR_SCO_SPO_LA_SEQ_TEM_IN_AVA_["eng"] = u"... As for the first hypothesis - in which events are independent and can be distinguished - we then should assume that, between one event and another, there is a \"moment\" in which time does not pass, but in which something happens that allows the next event to occur. We should assume that there is some sort of \"unmoved mover\" that, without being moved or \"caused\" by other events, it spontaneously manages to slide the timeline forward."
LDS._0986_04_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol3Tempo__SEG_LA_SEC_IPO_IN_CUI_GLI_EVE_SON_INS_E_IND_NON_SI_PRE_UN_FEN_DI_CAU_TRA_GLI_EVE_GLI_EVE_SON_IN_QUE_CAS_UN_UNI_BLO_CHE_ESI_SE_LA_PER_TE_DEL_TEM_RIS_QUI_PRO_DEG_ESS_VIV_UNA_PER_SIM_ALL_LET_DI_UN_LIB_CHE_PUR_ESI_PER_INT_VIE_COM_PAR_IN_DIV_MOM_DEL_TEM_["eng"] = u"... Concerning the second hypothesis, in which events are inseparable and indistinguishable, there is no cause-effect relationship between events. Events are, in this case, like a single block that \"always\" exists. The \"temporal\" perception of time is, therefore, typically ascribed to humans: a perception similar to the reading of a book that, although existing in its entirety, is partially and gradually understood at different times."
