LDS._0987_06_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol4Realt__MA_CI_CHE_AVV_QUA_SI__LI_DI_IMM_UNA_REA_AD_ESE_SOG_NON_DIF_MOL_DA_CI_CHE_PER_ATT_I_SEN_CI_DOV_IND_A_PEN_CHE_O_LIM__CRE_E_PLA_DAL_REA_EST_OPP_CHE_IN_QUA_MOD_NEL__GI_CON_LA_REA_["eng"] = u"... But what happens when one is \"free\" to imagine reality - for example by dreaming - is not that much different from what we perceive through the senses. This should lead us to think that either the imagination is created and shaped by external reality, or that the imagination already incorporates reality, someway..."
LDS._0987_07_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol4Realt__CON_DEL_PRI_CAS__LIN_DEL_PEN_SE_NON_COM_PRO_DEL_REA_IN_QUE_MOD_UN_IND_PRI_DI_SEN_E_CHE_NON_HA_MAI_FAT_ESP_DEL_REA_NON_POT_PRO_ALC_PEN_LIN_ESI_SEN_ESS_COS_E_FOR_SEN_ESS_VIV_LA_COS_DUN_NAS_E_SI_EVO_SOL_NEL_MOM_IN_CUI_ENT_IN_CON_CON_CI_CHE_STA_AL_DI_FUO_DI_LEI_["eng"] = u"... The consequence of the first scenario is the nonexistence of thought, if not as a product of reality. Accordingly, an individual lacking every sense who has never experienced reality could not produce any thoughts. One would simply exist without being conscious (and perhaps without living at all). Consciousness, therefore, would be born and would evolve only when it comes into contact with what is outside of it."
LDS._0987_08_LibroSullaCoscienzaVol4Realt__SEG_LA_SEC_IPO_IN_CUI_SI_SOS_CHE_LA_REA__CON_NEL_DED_CHE__LA_COS_A_PRO_LA_REA_CI_CHE_STA_FU_DI_NOI_SAR_UNA_SOR_DI_LIS_DI_RIC_CHE_COS_ATT_LIM_E_DAT_LEV_DET_DEL_REA_DOV_PEN_CHE_LE_LEG_FIS_CHE_LA_GOV_SIA_IN_VER_I_MEC_CON_CUI_LA_COS_SVI_I_SUI_PEN_["eng"] = u"... As far as the second hypothesis is concerned - in which it is argued that reality is contained in the imagination - we deduce that it is indeed consciousness that produces reality. What is \"out of us\", would be a sort of list of memories that we would build through imagination. And, given the deterministic evolution of reality, we should think that the physical laws that govern it are actually the mechanisms by which consciousness develops its thoughts."
